{"meta":{"spec_version":"0.3","created":"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z","author":"OpenChronology Demo"},"event":{"id":"medieval-era","type":"era","content":{"title":"The Middle Ages","date_label":"476 CE – 1500 CE","description":"The **Middle Ages** span from the fall of the Western Roman Empire in 476 CE to the dawn of the Renaissance around 1500 CE — roughly a thousand years of European history shaped by feudalism, the Catholic Church, dynastic conflict, plague, and the slow emergence of modernity.\n\nThe period is conventionally divided into the Early Middle Ages (476–1000), the High Middle Ages (1000–1300), and the Late Middle Ages (1300–1500). Each phase brought distinctive political structures, cultural achievements, and catastrophes that collectively forged the foundations of the modern West.","description_format":"markdown","tags":["medieval","europe","history","periodization"],"sources":[{"title":"The Middle Ages — Encyclopedia Britannica","url":"https://www.britannica.com/event/Middle-Ages"}]},"temporal":{"calendar":"gregorian","start_value":"476","end_value":"1500","precision":"year"},"significance":{"value":980,"temporal_scope":"centuries","geographic_scope":"europe"}}}
